\pard\f0\fs28\qc  {\b 56.       BASELLACEAE}
\par

\pard\f0\fs24\qc  Edit. S.M. Walters
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 Glabrous, perennial, twining herbs, usually fleshy. Leaves alternate, usually ovate with a more or less cordate base, entire. Flowers in spikes, racemes or racemose panicles, hermaphrodite. Sepals 2; petals 5; stamens 5, opposite petals. Ovary unilocular, with 3 styles and a single basal ovule. Fruit indehiscent, fleshy, surrounded by persistent sepals and petals.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 A small family, mainly in America, and not native to Europe.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28  {\b Basella alba} L., {\i Sp. Pl.} 390 (1753), a very fleshy perennial with flowers in spikes, probably a native of tropical Asia, is widely cultivated as a vegetable in S. Europe and occasionally escapes, but does not seem to be naturalized.
